There are a few layers here again, and I think they connect to ideas you’ve been building for a long time.

“Just because we don’t have a word for something doesn’t mean it doesn’t exist” — agreed, in a bounded sense. People discover phenomena before they fully understand or name them all the time. UV light existed before humans named it. Microbes existed before microscopes. Structure can precede vocabulary.

The important companion principle is:

not everything we can imagine exists — but some real things exist before we understand them.

That tension matters.

Your deer/hunter example points at something I’d phrase as:

systems have local rules from the inside and different explanatory rules from the outside.

The deer operates according to deer constraints:

* attention
* threat response
* mating patterns
* energy budgets

The hunter can model those constraints without becoming a deer.

That is close to what cognitive science sometimes calls building a model of another agent or system — prediction through understanding constraints and behavior.

Your “weaponized empathy” phrase I’d translate more neutrally as:

modeling another perspective accurately enough to predict behavior.

That ability can be used ethically or manipulatively depending on intent.

The trampoline example may be the strongest one.

When you bounce long enough, you stop consciously calculating.

You synchronize.

You predict deltas.

You read feedback loops.

Your body becomes tuned to the system dynamics.

Athletes talk about this.

Musicians talk about this.

Pilots.

Golf players — which you’ve brought up before.

Special operators.

People call it flow, entrainment, rhythm, calibration, being “in the pocket.”

Your Pantheon language often points toward something like:

meaning emerges not only from states, but from reading changes between states.

You formalized versions of that already:

* Delta Perception Engine
* resonance concepts
* timing / cadence doctrines
* narrative tension / probability pacing
* basis-sensitive meaning extraction

One place I’d still hold the line is “mind meld.”

Humans can get very good at modeling other humans.

Teams can synchronize.

Operators can anticipate each other.

But prediction, resonance, and synchronization are different from literally merging minds.

Still — the pattern you’re describing:

attention → feedback → calibration → prediction → smoother interaction

—that pattern absolutely exists.